# Need to define a function that will set the map for the scope of this study. 
# Match selected image's coordinate specs with min and max lat and long points
# This map will also help remove some outer lying points

def within_boundingbox_test(df, bound):
    return (df.pickup_longitude >= bound[0]) & (df.pickup_longitude <= bound[1]) & \
           (df.pickup_latitude >= bound[2]) & (df.pickup_latitude <= bound[3]) & \
           (df.dropoff_longitude >= bound[0]) & (df.dropoff_longitude <= bound[1]) & \
           (df.dropoff_latitude >= bound[2]) & (df.dropoff_latitude <= bound[3])
            
# Load image of NYC map
BoundingBox = (-74.5, -72.8, 40.5, 41.8) #add some space to the min and max values

#Need to define a function that will plot points on the map for this study
#Image serves as the background

def plot_on_map(df, BB, nyc_map, s=10, alpha=0.2):
    fig, axs = pl.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(22,16))
    axs[0].scatter(df.pickup_longitude, df.pickup_latitude, zorder=1, alpha=alpha, c='r', s=s)
    axs[0].set_xlim((BB[0], BB[1]))
    axs[0].set_ylim((BB[2], BB[3]))
    axs[0].set_title('Pickup locations')
    axs[0].imshow(nyc_map, zorder=0, extent=BB)

    axs[1].scatter(df.dropoff_longitude, df.dropoff_latitude, zorder=1, alpha=alpha, c='r', s=s)
    axs[1].set_xlim((BB[0], BB[1]))
    axs[1].set_ylim((BB[2], BB[3]))
    axs[1].set_title('Dropoff locations')
    axs[1].imshow(nyc_map, zorder=0, extent=BB)

#FEATURE ENGINEERING - Distance

#longitude and latitude are futile measures without understanding the distance between the point
#The distance between can be engineered using a formula
#distance on a map is more than a simple Euclidean distance calculation across coordinates. 
#The Haversine formula is necessary.

def Haversine_distance(lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2):
    p = 0.017453292519943295 # Pi/180
    a = 0.5 - np.cos((lat2 - lat1) * p)/2 + np.cos(lat1 * p) * np.cos(lat2 * p) * (1 - np.cos((lon2 - lon1) * p)) / 2
    return 0.6213712 * 12742 * np.arcsin(np.sqrt(a))

#FEATURE ENGINEERING - Distance measure Manhattan distance

#The Manhattan distance gives another measure of distance which uses a method that takes into account in more general terms the path that the distance takes
#The Manhattan formula is necessary.

def Manhattan_distance(lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2):
    
    return abs(lat1-lat2)+abs(lon1-lon2)

#define the coordinates for the different boroughs of New York. These are only accurate to the accuracy of Google Maps

nyc_boroughs = {
    'Manhattan':{
        'min_lng':-74.0483,
        'min_lat':40.6832,
        'max_lng':-73.9010,
        'max_lat':40.8821
    },
    
    'Queens':{
        'min_lng':-73.9635,
        'min_lat':40.5430,
        'max_lng':-73.7009,
        'max_lat':40.8001

    },

    'Brooklyn':{
        'min_lng':-74.0422,
        'min_lat':40.5710,
        'max_lng':-73.8333,
        'max_lat':40.7398

    },

    'Bronx':{
        'min_lng':-73.9339,
        'min_lat':40.7856,
        'max_lng':-73.7653,
        'max_lat':40.9176

    },

    'Staten_Island':{
        'min_lng':-74.2558,
        'min_lat':40.4960,
        'max_lng':-74.0522,
        'max_lat':40.6490

    }
    
}

#define a function that grabs the borough based on the coordinates given
def getBorough(lat,lng):
    
    bor=nyc_boroughs.keys()
    for location in bor:
        if lat>=nyc_boroughs[location]['min_lat'] and lat<=nyc_boroughs[location]['max_lat'] and lng>=nyc_boroughs[location]['min_lng'] and lng<=nyc_boroughs[location]['max_lng']:
            return location
    return 'outside of boroughs'

#below are functions that are defined to facilitate an easier process in creating graphs and visualizations
#functions aggregate by finding the mean of the given "value" variable and assign them according to a "grouper" variable

def plotbar(data,grouper,value,aggregate='mean'):
        pl.figure(figsize=(16,10))
        agg_data=data.groupby([grouper])[value].agg(aggregate).reset_index().rename(columns={value:aggregate+'_'+value})
        pl.subplot(1,2,1)
        sb.barplot(x=grouper,y=aggregate+'_'+value,data=agg_data,color='maroon').set_title(aggregate+'_'+value+" vs "+grouper)
        
def plotline(data,grouper,value,aggregate='mean'):
        pl.figure(figsize=(16,10))
        agg_data=data.groupby([grouper])[value].agg(aggregate).reset_index().rename(columns={value:aggregate+'_'+value})
        pl.subplot(1,2,1)
        sb.lineplot(x=grouper,y=aggregate+'_'+value,data=agg_data,color='maroon').set_title(aggregate+'_'+value+" vs "+grouper)

def location_map(loc, name, range=1.5): #1.5 miles is a fair distance boundary
    # select all datapoints with dropoff location within range of airport
    fig, axs = pl.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 5))
    idx = (Haversine_distance(df_train.dropoff_latitude, df_train.dropoff_longitude, loc[0], loc[1]) < range)
    df_train[idx].fare_amount.hist(bins=100, ax=axs[0])
    axs[0].set_xlabel('fare $USD')
    axs[0].set_title('Histogram dropoff location within {} miles of {}'.format(range, name))
        
location_map(jfk, 'JFK Airport')
